      <div class="page-wrapper">
        <h2>General Banquet Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How far in advance should I start planning a sports banquet?</h3>
          <p>We recommend starting at least 8 weeks before your event. This allows time for venue booking, custom orders (especially centerpieces, which require 2-3 weeks for design and production), and proper promotion to families. Starting early also means less stress as the event approaches.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How long should a sports banquet last?</h3>
          <p>Most successful sports banquets run 2 to 2.5 hours. A typical structure: 30 minutes for social/gathering time, 45-60 minutes for dinner, 5-10 minutes for a season highlight slideshow, 30-45 minutes for awards and speeches, and 10-15 minutes for closing remarks. Keeping it under 2.5 hours helps maintain energy and attention.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is a reasonable budget per person for a sports banquet?</h3>
          <p>The average high school sports banquet costs between $15-35 per person for food, venue, and basic decorations. Premium options with custom centerpieces, higher-end catering, and professional photography can range from $35-65 per person. Many programs fund this through ticket sales, booster club contributions, or fundraising.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Decoration Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What should I put on the center of my banquet tables?</h3>
          <p>The centerpiece is the focal point of each table. Popular options include custom 3D printed sports centerpieces (designed for your sport and colors), team memorabilia displays, photo collage arrangements, or seasonal flowers in team colors. The best centerpieces are visible above the table, photograph well, and reflect your team's identity.</p>
          <p><a href="https://lakeshore-gift.myshopify.com/collections/all" target="_blank">Browse custom sports centerpiece options →</a></p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many centerpieces do I need for my banquet?</h3>
          <p>Plan for one centerpiece per table. For round tables that seat 8-10 people, one centerpiece is sufficient. For long rectangular tables, you may want one every 4-6 feet. A good rule of thumb: if you have 20 tables, you need 15-20 centerpieces (order a few extras for the head table and registration area).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What are the most popular decoration themes for sports banquets?</h3>
          <p>The most popular themes include team colors and logos, "Hall of Fame" (vintage sports memorabilia), "Season in Review" (action photos and highlights), and "Hollywood Red Carpet" (formal celebration). The key is choosing a theme that matches your program's personality and budget.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Senior Night Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>When should senior night be held?</h3>
          <p>Senior night is typically scheduled during the last home game or match of the regular season. This allows the entire community to participate and gives seniors a proper send-off in their competitive environment. Some programs also hold a separate senior recognition event if the game schedule doesn't allow it.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What should I include in a senior night ceremony?</h3>
          <p>A well-structured senior night includes: welcome and introduction, team season highlights, individual senior introductions with personal anecdotes, coach's remarks, optional parent/senior speeches, presentation of senior gifts, and closing remarks with a team photo. The entire ceremony should run 20-30 minutes.</p>
          <p><a href="/senior-night/">Read the full Senior Night Guide →</a></p>
        </div>

        <h2>Award Ceremony Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many award categories should I have?</h3>
          <p>Aim for 8-12 awards that balance performance recognition with character recognition. This ensures every athlete has a meaningful award while keeping the ceremony manageable. Key categories include MVP, Most Improved, Coach's Award, Sportsmanship, and Academic honors.</p>
          <p><a href="/award-ceremony/">Read the full Award Ceremony Guide →</a></p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Should every athlete receive an award?</h3>
          <p>Yes — every athlete should receive recognition. This can be as simple as a certificate of participation or a varsity letter. The goal is to ensure every athlete feels valued while still creating special moments for standout achievements. Balance is key.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Graduation Party Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How far in advance should I start planning a graduation party?</h3>
          <p>Start planning at least 8 weeks before graduation day. This gives you time to book venues (which fill up quickly in May and June), order custom centerpieces and decorations, arrange catering, and send invitations. Custom 3D printed centerpieces need 2-3 weeks for production.</p>
          <p><a href="/graduation-party/">Read the full Graduation Party Guide →</a></p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Where can I find custom sports banquet centerpieces?</h3>
